WEBVTT

00:01.900 --> 00:05.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight:
There was a time when summer
TV was largely confined

00:06.433 --> 00:08.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to reruns.

00:08.366 --> 00:10.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But that has changed
dramatically in the
world of streaming video.

00:10.166 --> 00:14.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, in fact, a new summer
season is under way.

00:14.166 --> 00:16.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has a look.

00:16.266 --> 00:19.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The summer season
has changed so much, that it's
now when some of the best-known

00:19.166 --> 00:21.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
shows debut new episodes.

00:21.200 --> 00:25.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
High on that list, the fantasy
series "Game of Thrones," which
run the Emmy for best drama

00:25.600 --> 00:27.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and is back on HBO.

00:27.200 --> 00:30.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
"Orange Is the New Black" will
air new episodes on Netflix.

00:30.600 --> 00:34.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
NBC returns with its
surprise comedy hit
"The Carmichael Show."

00:34.333 --> 00:38.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And there are plenty
of new options such
as "Claws," a Southern
crime drama with a comic

00:38.900 --> 00:43.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
edge that comes to TNT, a show
about the founding of the first
women's wrestling federation

00:45.900 --> 00:49.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
called "GLOW" on Netflix, and a
Showtime drama about struggling
comics in the 1970s called

00:50.400 --> 00:52.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
"I'm Dying Up Here."

00:52.500 --> 00:56.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Two TV critics, I hope they're
not dying where we are talking
to them, from all of television.

00:56.833 --> 01:01.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're going to help us
sort through the season, Eric
Deggans of NPR and Sonia Saraiya

01:01.600 --> 01:02.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of "Variety."

01:02.600 --> 01:04.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thanks, both, for joining us.

01:04.066 --> 01:06.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't know how you keep up
with this, but help us out here.

01:06.300 --> 01:10.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
First of all, Eric,
summer season, does it
actually mean anything?

01:10.633 --> 01:12.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Is there any rhyme
or reason anymore?

01:12.733 --> 01:16.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIC DEGGANS, National Public
Radio: Well, you know, TV is
a business that loves habits.

01:16.000 --> 01:19.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, for the
broadcasters especially,
there is a summer season.

01:19.666 --> 01:24.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think it's less so for
the cable nets, and it's
even less so for the
streamers like Netflix,

01:26.133 --> 01:29.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
which seem to churn out a new
series just about every week.

01:29.133 --> 01:32.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there is a sense that the
TV season is slowing down a
little bit, and we're seeing

01:32.433 --> 01:36.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shows that are less than
marquee shows debuting
during the next few months.

01:36.533 --> 01:39.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
